Reply <a href="/eq/board/message?board.id=clericbalance&message.id=10797#M10797">29</a> of 44
</span>

			<br><img src="/i/p.gif" width=1 height=6><br>
			<span style="font-size: 8pt; font-weight: normal;">
			
					Viewed 624 times<br>
					
			</span>
			
		</td>
		
		<td rowspan=2 bgcolor="#050A0E" width=1><img src="/i/p.gif" height=1 width=1 border=0 alt=""><br></td>
	
		<td colspan=2 class="msg_text_cell" width="100%" valign=top style="text-align: justify; 
		" 
			>
			<BR>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<HR>
Saroc_Luclin wrote:<BR><BR>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<HR>
brum wrote:<BR><BR>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
<HR>

<P></P>
<P>Saroc_Luclin wrote:<BR>I believe the desire is to have that state be Group and/or Raid wide, so that if anyone in group has aggro, the bonuses don't apply, ditto for raid. </P>
<P><FONT color=#cc0000>why does it ahve to be group wide? if a cleric is willing to set out the fight and not heal or take any action except med, why shouldnt he get individual better mana regen. If a wizard forgoes any spelll casting during a round of fighting--he sacrices inputting dps so why shouldnt he get increased mana regen. It is a matter of a group or raid making a choice. Hey bill--set this one out and dont get aggro-we will need you FM on the next one.</FONT><BR><BR>The Aggro dumping classes are a thorn in the plans too. I doubt the Dev's want the necro's 'simply' raid disbanding, FDing during an encounter and medding to full faster than anyone else. <FONT color=#cc0000>/why not---they wont be doing any damage this fight then? If it works like the sitting health regen-they will have to be off aggro for awhile for it to really benefit them. </FONT>(Or Monk's doing the same for endurance). So some way has to be developed to set up that 'non combat' state, while at the same time not wrecking in game concepts like FD, Bard Fade, monk FDing, etc. Nor even a cleric going OOM, camping, logging back in and staying out of raid till he's medded to full. <BR><BR>Pulling would be an issue as well. Ideally you would want the faster regen while someone was out pulling, but as soon as that person got aggro, everyone loses that regen rate. You could see people disbanding the puller from the group, and reinviting while the pull is inc. <FONT color=#cc0000>hence why it should be individual aggro---If you are on aggro whatsoever from taking an action (not just proximity here) then you dont get increased regen. But if you dont take any action (hence dont break concentration) you get increasingly better regen.<BR></FONT><BR>You'll notice that with Chest rewards, if you have aggro (from even a trap annoyingly), you can't loot. But if someone hasn't gotten aggro in your group, they can loot the chest. Which means that the Aggro check code is not Groupwide.<BR></P>
<P>
<HR>

<P></P></BLOCKQUOTE><BR>
<DIV></DIV><BR>
<HR>
</BLOCKQUOTE><BR><BR><BR><BR>Just as an addendum.<BR><BR>The main concern the Dev's have with increasing the In-Battle regen rates too much is the risk it will throw off balancing for existing encounters. Health, unlike Mana/End, other than giving the healer heart attacks (and unless you are the MA), makes little difference whether you are at 30Health or Full Health. So having a DPS sit out a battle to regen health faster is not really a good tactic.<BR><BR>But with Mana, you start getting returns much faster when you start playing with the regen rates in a non-trivial fashion. A caster who's OOM and a caster who has 20M have a world of difference in what they have available to them. (I may not be saying this clearly).<BR><BR>Lets take a cleric who is completely OOM, and who has a regen rate of 80 mana per tick while sitting. (And ignore all other factors like focii).<BR><BR>Under the current system, in order to gain 400 mana, enough to cast CH, it would take this cleric 30 seconds to regen enough mana to cast again.<BR><BR>Now, lets consider a system where your mana regen doubles every tick you are sitting.<BR>At 6 seconds, the cleric has 80 mana. <BR>At 12 seconds, the cleric has 240 mana.<BR>At 18 seconds, the cleric has 560 mana, more than enough for CH. CH is now castable in 2/3rds the time than before, and the CLR ends up with 160 mana to spare (not counting Focus effects).<BR>(Or you can keep sitting and get:<BR>At 24 seconds, the cleric has 1200 mana (3+ CH's)<BR>At 30 seconds, the cleric has 2480 mana.<BR>At 36 seconds, the cleric has 5040 mana, and is probably 50M or so by now.<BR>(This is an extreme; such a rate would probably be too much)<BR><BR>Or lets consider a system where you get your original regen rate again for every tick.<BR>At 6 seconds, you have 80mana<BR>At 12 seconds you have 240mana<BR>At 18 seconds you have 480mana, and are ready to CH again.<BR>At 24 seconds you have 800mana<BR>At 30 secodns you have 1200mana <BR>At 36 seconds you have 1680mana<BR>At 42 seconds you have 2240 mana and at 20-30M roughly<BR>At 48 seconds you have 2880 mana<BR>At 54 seconds you have 3600 mana<BR>At 1 minute, you have 4400 mana, and approaching 40-50M. <BR><BR>A more reasonable rate, but probably still too fast for in battle regen, since if you can stay seated for 30 seconds during the fight, a cleric could get 3 CHeals worth of mana (Probably 4+ CHeals given Focus effects, AA's, and standing/mount regen while casting considerations) Many clerics would be nearly full mana after 90 seconds or so.<BR><BR>Even if you double the period between rate increases, you're still looking at 2 CH's in 30-36 seconds, and 3-4 CH's in 42 seconds.<BR><BR>The challenge would be to find an increasing regen rate formula that works for most/all levels of all classes which does not also destablize existing encounters for those at the appropriate levels to handle them. <BR><BR>Consider for example, General Reparm in PoFire (I think I got his name right) with a level/AA/gear appropriate raid. His difficulty would be diminished if the first wave of healers and nukers could be back in for the final stages of the fight with suitable mana pools because they were able to med that fast enough out of range of his drain.<BR><BR>So instead of taking up that particular challenge (and the balancing issues it could cause for future expansions), the Dev's seem to prefer to try and find a different solution, like trying to add in a "In-Battle State" to the game, or maybe some other solution they haven't breathed a word of. (For all we know they are trying to come up with a suitable mana/end regen formula but haven't hinted at it to keep speculation low)<BR>
<HR>
</BLOCKQUOTE><BR>
<DIV></DIV>Instead of "out of combat" regen kicking in&nbsp;at the first tick why not have the person wait 1 full minute before it kicks in.&nbsp; This way the system knows the toon is in mana regen mode and not trying to exploit the system.	
		</td></tr>
